3C's

  • Fully Prepped for and Execute Successful Sprint Planning
  • BLN RESTOCK Desktop Development pushed to PE qadb
  • Get everything organized and back in a solid work routine after last few weeks

John thanks for championing and spearheading this. 

 

Everyone we really need to give BLN some love and re-earn some of the equity we've lost. They're our second largest customer and we're entering into a negotiation year with them 

 

I realize juggling development on our new platform, taking care of BPF/BLN, GP, and the like is taxing and difficult... and acknowledge this takes a lot of strategic conversation/tradeoffs, but this is our lot until we can finish the new platform and get everyone migrated. We have to take care of the existing customers on legacy apps that are cutting the checks for the new.

 

Our future stack will be scalable and much easier to support, in the meantime we have to take care of our current frankenstein and build as much as we can in the margin

BK Call Results 2/2/2026

I reviewed our "Spring Readiness" discussions with BK Today. See below for outline.

Call notes on his key issues

  • He seemed ok with the Restock plans and readiness.
  • He really dialed into Forecast and Produce and the issues they have experienced with them.
  • His focus on "lost trust with Silver Fern" and "pain points" centered around Produce and Forecast.
  • He mentioned the mums and the poinsettias issues - although admitting the points issues was mostly likely more on them than us.
  • He repeated that they have experienced pain points as both "Data" and "Calculations" issues.
  • He stressed that they find errors (talking about calculations) that we should catch in our tools.
  • He didn't blame Nathan but referred to several times that "Nathan has to do some behind the scenes magic..." to get them working (Speaking specifically about Produce).
  • He said that when things happen, we are responsive. But too many, too costly things happen.
  • He chided me for our lack of testing.  "how does this happen"
  • He expressed frustrations about how the issues with the tools cost them time, and what I will restate here as "time to visibility".

My Take

  • I know sometimes he can come across as hyperbolic, but I think he was expressing genuine concern about perception inside Bell of our tools, and their belief in our ability to release quality, performant products to drive their business forward.
  • The honeymoon of the great results they got last year with our tools is totally gone. 
  • We must go and re-earn their trust and demonstrate results, and it must be done on our legacy apps.

Immediate Action Plan

  • BK suggested a "digital round table' with some of the parties to get the current experiences and pain point details equally understood. I told him we would support that and he is checking calendars to see when we can potentially get the relevant parties on a call and will get back with me.
  • Need an OPs review of this situation to start any additional review / planning, addressing now.
  • Once we meet with them, we recapitulate our plans and implementations.

 

 

Spring Readiness Outline - BLN -26

  1. Restock
    1. 4 Quality of lIfe Updates Isaac/team is working on
      1. Option for Override to Adhere to Availability
      2. Fix Promotion Group Logic When Committing a Single Item/Kit (Initial Allocation vs. Redistribution)
      3. Fix LastSold Column showing Incorrect Date
      4. Add Promotion Group OnHands Column to Write Orders
  2. BLN Restock DB Server
    1. Data pipeline flowing
    2. Plenty of capacity for data and CPU
    3. Expanded Monitoring for server issues in place
  3. Produce
    1. Nathan has improved automation for the consolidation data process for spring. Should go very quickly this year compared to last and not take Nathan much time (has some Claude help he is designing for this)
  4. Forecast
    1. Nothing new at this time.
  5. AI REPL
    1. Update on QuickSand
      1. Data Ingestion and Training Pipeline on AWS working
      2. Weather - All NOAA weather stations in US for last 5 years in place
      3. Clustering - Stores / SKUs (Data columns Item Master) - working / being analyzed
      4. Model Training starting
CC is already doing that. have you used for any large projects recently? It's so much more effective than it used to be
Makes total sense. The video was super helpful on how to think about Agentic/Assistant AI, generally and why demand for something like this was/is so high
"OpenClaw is useful because it is dangerous"

Yeah, we should not use OpenClaw based on the security holes and other risks he mentions. I mean, the crypto attack that occurred during a 10 second window, is the way the internet is. There are millions of apps out there just watching the web for vulnerabilities in your system. We need to wait until these things are solved.
Yes, definitely watch. It was much more helpful than the hours I spent on X reading about it this weekend
Yes, I just talked to the team about it. I think it is too soon to use this. It essentially is like Claude Code without guardrails. I'll watch the video to see if my thinking changes any.
His meta thought around agentic AI and security is very insightful. Starts around 8:30
Love it. Now tell Claude to generate a beautiful HTML and let her cook.

I plan to present this to the team in our Tech Weekly today. It is based on the behavior and action Scott put forth helping Bonnie with Material/Finish Users Assignments Auth. Let me know if you have any feedback.

love this 

 

If your work:

  • Reduced ambiguity
  • Increased system resilience
  • Eliminated future risk
  • Earned customer confidence

Then you met the bar.

If it merely “fulfilled the request,” you did not.

Mood.log — Weekly Summary Jan 26 – Feb 2, 2026

Good: 6 (67%) Ok: 3 (33%) Bad: 0 (0%)

Total: 9 responses

Orders are priced based on the ordered quantity. If the acknowledged quantity differs from the ordered quantity, pricing is recalculated accordingly; if the shipped quantity is updated, pricing is updated to reflect it. 

 

Overrides can happen at 2 levels, item level, OR order level, meaning i can have an override price and that will be what is used regardless of what qty is shipped on an order, still, the qty at each stage can affect the total, i.e if the customer originally ordered 5, but i only shipped 3 pricing will reflect 3 shipped units. 

 

Currently, statuses are at the whole order level, meaning you cannot partially ship or acknowledge orders; you will be able to do this long term, but not at this point in the process.

Nathan ^ need help getting to a more clear answer on this so that I can get back to them (preferably sometime tomorrow). I don't have the product understanding to sort through this ... can you all discuss and let me know what correct wording for customer would be?
Doesn't sound like fulfill allows for Overides on the fly

Nathans answer implies that the whole order is either acknowledged or shipped.  A status of the order.  GP allows each line item to be either shipped or acknowledged.  The extended total of the line item will adust from that.

here is the answer Nathan sent over for the first one "Yes, you will be able to have pricing set at either level. It will recalculate depending on the status of the order. So acknowledge would be at the acknowledge level, and ship would be at the ship level."..... I'm not clear on whether this is actually addressing her question or if it will be what she expects... any thoughts?

I didn't see the setup on the demo.  It is possible there were no quantity breaks on the demo prices.   GrowPoint orders have 3 qty.  Ordered = what the customer wanted.  Acknowledged = what you said they could have,  and Shipped = What did they get.  Prices are calculated off the Ack quantity unless\until a shipped qty is entered.
Ekstrom Prices off of Acknowledged and extends totals on Shipped

Pricing is done various ways in Growpoint - By Order/Acknowledge or Shipped.  If the Selling price is Overridden on the fly the extended will take the override not the original selling.  We also show the Original price next to the Selling so you can see the difference after the override.

Got these question from a Growpoint customer re: the fulfill demo... can you all provide any input on answers?

 

We are re-watching the video and had a couple of questions in the pricing section. Viewing that you can manually edit the acknowledge and the shipping fields, but the line total did not change as the quantities changed. Was that just a bug and will it total from the shipping quantity (if populated) when fixed and total from the acknowledgment column if not shipped yet?

 

Also, when the override price is manually updated, the price column also updated. Again, is this a bug or will the price column stay stagnant, and the line total will drive from the override price. And will the overrride price be dynamic eventually to choose either a $ amount or a %? We are looking for these options to be by customer/by invoice and not by just by plant.

The goal for our customer meetings over the next couple of weeks is to gather as much information as possible about how they use GrowPoint so that we can begin to evaluate when FULFILL will be ready for their use. I'd like to avoid pulling up FULFILL if possible, they can attend the group demos to see the product. But, it's not in a state where it's an efficient use of time to nitpick small things in FULFILL. Would like to keep conversation focused on what their workflows are, what missing features will be blockers for their transition, etc.

 

Let me know if you have any questions or ideas on how to make these meetings flow smoothly, we'll have a lot of them over the next year
